title: For Sale/Trade:  Smith & Wesson Model 1, 2nd issue
postcontent:
Hi folks, I'm selling a rare S&W model 1, 2nd issue, made between 1860 & 1868. These are few and rarely found in good enough condition that they can still safely be fired. This one is definitely in that good of condition, (Though I don't shoot it of course). The timing is good, springs are still strong, fins on the cylinder are in great shape, etc..  As you can see, the nickle plating on the cylinder is mostly gone but for maybe 20%. The rest of the gun retains I'd say around 90% of the nickel finish and definitely shows it’s age but is obviously all original. Overall this is a great piece for the collection. W.A.S.P. Treated Barrel
(Weapon Armament Surface Protection) is a salt bath ferritic nitrocarburizing surface conversion process or more commonly referred to as nitriding. The nitriding conversion is applied to the barrel inside and out, along with the front sight base on our LE rifles and uppers. Nitriding offers improved wear, abrasion, and corrosion resistance when compared to hard chrome lining or phosphating. 

Unlike chrome lining, where the chrome is built up on the surface, nitriding converts the surface without the risk of dimensional build up. CMMG Pioneered the use of this nitriding process on AR barrels and has been using it for many years.
